{% extends "_base.html.jinja" %}

{# The CFD only uses the Period (window); the reference period drives
   aging thresholds + forecasts, not the CFD — so hide it here. #}
{% block filter_bar %}
  <nav class="filter-bar" aria-label="Filters">
    <div class="container">
      {% with hide_reference = True %}
        {% include "_partials/period_filter.html.jinja" %}
      {% endwith %}
    </div>
  </nav>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <style>
    /* The tile owns the panel's offset parent so the panel can
       float against the chart's coordinates, not the page's. */
    .cfd-tile-wrap { position: relative; margin-bottom: 0.4rem; }
    .cfd-tile-wrap > .metric { margin: 0; }

    .cfd-panel-float {
      position: absolute;
      top: 3.2rem;
      width: 12.5rem;
      z-index: 4;
      background: var(--surface);
      border: 0.0625rem solid var(--border);
      border-radius: 0.5rem;
      padding: 0.6rem 0.75rem;
      font-size: 0.8rem;
      box-shadow: 0 0.125rem 0.5rem rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.06);
      /* Don't intercept chart hover/click — the click handler lives
         on the SVG itself, and clicking the panel would mean the
         reader has to aim past it. */
      pointer-events: none;
      transition: left 80ms ease;
    }
    .cfd-panel-float.is-pinned {
      outline: 0.125rem solid var(--p-500);
      outline-offset: -0.125rem;
    }
    .cfd-panel-pin {
      font-size: 0.65rem; color: var(--p-700);
      text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em;
      margin: 0 0 0.3rem 0;
    }
    .cfd-panel-date {
      font-family: var(--head-font); font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--p-600); margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
    }
    .cfd-panel-table {
      width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-bottom: 0.45rem;
    }
    .cfd-panel-table th {
      text-align: left; font-size: 0.65rem; text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.05em; color: var(--muted);
      border-bottom: 0.0625rem solid var(--border); padding: 0.12rem 0;
    }
    .cfd-panel-table td { padding: 0.12rem 0; }
    .cfd-panel-table td:last-child {
      text-align: right; font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
    }
    .cfd-panel-flow {
      border-top: 0.0625rem dashed var(--border); padding-top: 0.3rem;
    }
    .cfd-panel-flow td:first-child { color: var(--muted); }
    /* Narrow viewports: the floating overlay falls back to a static
       block below the chart so it doesn't crowd a phone-width chart. */
    @media (max-width: 56rem) {
      .cfd-panel-float {
        position: static; width: 100%; box-sizing: border-box;
        margin-top: 0.75rem; left: auto !important; right: auto;
      }
    }
  </style>

  {% with summary = {"title": "Cumulative Flow", "headline": cfd.headline} %}
    {% include "_partials/metric_summary.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  <div class="cfd-tile-wrap">
    {% with mode = 'detail', data = cfd %}
      {% include "_partials/cfd_tile.html.jinja" %}
    {% endwith %}
    <aside id="cfd-hover-panel" class="cfd-panel-float" aria-live="polite"></aside>
  </div>

  {% if cfd.daily %}
  <section class="ds-section" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
    <h2>Flow balance — daily arrivals vs departures</h2>
    <p class="filter-hint" style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
      When the two lines track each other the system is balanced;
      arrivals persistently above departures means WIP is growing.
    </p>
    <div id="flow-balance-chart" class="metric-chart"></div>
    <script>
      (function () {
        const spec = {{ flow_balance(cfd) | safe }};
        function go() {
          vegaEmbed("#flow-balance-chart", window.applyTheme(spec), {
            actions: false, renderer: "svg"
          }).catch(function (err) {
            document.getElementById("flow-balance-chart").innerText =
              "Chart render failed: " + err;
          });
        }
        if (window.requestAnimationFrame) requestAnimationFrame(go);
        else go();
      })();
    </script>
  </section>
  {% endif %}

  <details class="detail-extras">
    <summary>Help · how to read, what to do next</summary>
    <h2>How to read this</h2>
    <p>
      Each band is a stage. Its height on a given date is the
      count of items currently in that stage. Bands stack in
      workflow order top-to-bottom; total stack height = items
      currently in the system.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Slope of the <em>top</em> = arrival rate. Slope of
        the <em>bottom</em> = throughput. Horizontal distance
        between them at any date ≈ lead time.</li>
      <li>A widening band for one stage = WIP piling up there,
        a likely bottleneck. A flattening band = work
        evaporating without progressing.</li>
      <li>Arrivals and departures tracking each other = balanced
        flow. The flow-balance chart below is the easier read
        for spotting the days WIP actually grew.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Possible next steps</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>If a single band stays consistently widest, set a
        <strong>WIP limit</strong> on that stage and review it
        weekly.</li>
      <li>Hover the flow-balance chart on a deficit run to find
        the exact date WIP started accumulating.</li>
      <li>If the top band is steepening while the bottom is flat:
        stop intake or split work before cycle time degrades.</li>
    </ul>
  </details>

  <a class="back-link" href="{{ ("/workflows/" ~ contract.name ~ "/") | keep_filters }}">← Back to dashboard</a>
{% endblock %}
